<div id="police-report-some-looting-in-downtown-ferguson" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#police-report-some-looting-in-downtown-ferguson">10:43 P.M.</a></span><strong>Police Report Some Looting in Downtown Ferguson</strong></h5>
</div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<div class="w480">
<figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/25/us/FERGUSONBLOG-CAR2/FERGUSONBLOG-CAR2-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
<div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/25/us/FERGUSONBLOG-CAR2/FERGUSONBLOG-CAR2-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/25/us/FERGUSONBLOG-CAR2/FERGUSONBLOG-CAR2-blog480.jpg" id="100000003254116" width="480" height="320" alt="A group of protesters vandalize a police vehicle after the announcement of the grand jury decision in Ferguson, Mo."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div>
<figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A group of protesters vandalize a police vehicle after the announcement of the grand jury decision in Ferguson, Mo.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> David Goldman/Associated Press</span></figcaption>
</figure>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The St. Louis County Police said that it had received reports of looting along West Florissant Avenue in Ferguson.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Soon after the department posted the assertion on Twitter, officers in riot gear stood in front of businesses, including a McDonald&#8217;s and a chain discount store.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Some protesters blocked the street, and a police officer warned them to move or face arrest.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>ALAN BLINDER</em></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="shots-fired-outside-ferguson-police-station" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#shots-fired-outside-ferguson-police-station">10:40 P.M.</a></span><strong>Shots Fired Outside Ferguson Police Station</strong></h5>
</div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As the police used tear gas to disperse a crowd in front of the Ferguson police station, the sound of gunfire could be heard and it appeared that the shots were not fired by the police.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>MANNY FERNANDEZ</em></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="sharpton-on-judicial-system-flawed-and-suspect" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#sharpton-on-judicial-system-flawed-and-suspect">10:26 P.M.</a></span><strong>Sharpton on Judicial System: &#8216;Flawed&#8217; and &#8216;Suspect&#8217;</strong></h5>
</div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Rev. Al Sharpton was brief and succinct, and said that while the news of the grand jury&#8217;s decision was expected, &#8220;it hurts nonetheless.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Beside him stood members of Eric Garner&#8217;s family, who silently sucked in their lips and tried to fight back tears. Mr. Garner died after being placed in a choke hold by a New York City police officer.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Sharpton called the judicial system in Ferguson &#8220;deeply flawed&#8221; and &#8220;very suspect.&#8221; An example was how prosecutor Robert P. McCulloch explained that it was legal to use deadly force against a fleeing felon, while he also explained that Michael Brown&#8217;s crime was stealing cigarillos from a corner store.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;That qualifies as a felon?&#8221; Mr. Sharpton said. &#8220;You are trying to describe a shoplifter as a fleeing felon.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He said that he would push for a federal investigation and prosecution. An example of the difference, he said, is that it is legal to shoot a fleeing felon under Missouri law, but not federal law.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He also brought up both Mr. Garner and, from just last week, Akai Gurley, who also died at the hands of  a New York City police officer who officials said accidentally fired his gun inside a darkened stairwell.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;We are dealing with the same attitudes of Ferguson,&#8221; he said, &#8220;right here in the city.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He said he would speak more from Ferguson tomorrow.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>NATE SCHWEBER</em></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="police-use-tear-gas-to-disperse-crowd" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#police-use-tear-gas-to-disperse-crowd">10:27 P.M.</a></span><strong>Ferguson Police Use Tear Gas to Disperse Crowd</strong></h5>
</div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">About a block from the police station on South Florissant Road, officers deployed tear gas to disperse a crowd of demonstrators who were hurling rocks at them and destroying and shattering the windows of parked police cruisers.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I was struck, a glance, nothing more, on the leg by a small rock. I felt the tear gas too, and am still feeling it. Some protesters hurled the tear-gas canisters back at the police.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Earlier, protesters shattered the windows of a few businesses on South Florissant Road, including a Mexican restaurant.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>MANNY FERNANDEZ</em></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="a-call-for-action-in-atlanta" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#a-call-for-action-in-atlanta">10:19 P.M.</a></span><strong>A Call for Action in Atlanta</strong></h5>
</div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">ATLANTA â Civil rights leaders called for a protest in Atlanta on Monday night. But the Michael Brown decision came late in the evening, and what was supposed to be a protest became an angry news conference by civil rights leaders. They grimaced, and some cried.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWell, itâs a frustration that I have not become immune to,â said Vincent Fort, a Georgia state senator, who is black.  âItâs a frequent feeling,â he said, that the system âdoesnât work.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Rev. Markel Hutchins, a civil rights leader, called Monday âone of the saddest days in recent American history.â  The system, he said, âsystematically fails to protect the lives of young black men.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Hutchins told black parents to put their arms around their sons. âIf you donât look like Michael Brown, or have a son or a grandson or a cousin who looks like Michael Brown, you will never understand how we feel tonight,â he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Heather Washington brought her 14-year-old daughter, Precious Imagbe. âI canât believe that here in the 21st century, we are still marching,â Ms. Washington said. âMy parents marched, and now weâre here doing it again.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>RICHARD FAUSSET</em></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="brown-family-says-legal-system-failed-them" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#brown-family-says-legal-system-failed-them">10:23 P.M.</a></span><strong>Brown Family Lawyer Says Legal System Failed Them</strong></h5>
</div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Benjamin Crump, a lawyer who represents the Brown family, sat waiting for interviews in a downtown St Louis hotel, watching the prosecutorâs news conference on his phone.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIâm going to spend the night trying to explain to my clients about the legal system, because they believe it failed them,â he said when asked what was next, âand that the killer of an unarmed child is not going to be held accountable.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Crump said that the family learned about the grand jury decision âabout 10 minutes before they told the world.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThey donât trust this prosecutor, they never did from the beginning,â he said. âAnd they are going to try to see if they can do something to get some positive change out of this because they understand this system needs to be changed. If we keep this system the same way, we keep getting the same results.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He added that he and the Brown family would be exploring their legal options. Among the changes Mr. Crump said the family would be pushing for now was the wearing of video-cameras by police officers and the appointment of special prosecutors in cases of shootings involving police officers.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>CAMPBELL ROBERTSON</em></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="a-growing-crowd-in-denver-2" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#a-growing-crowd-in-denver-2">10:09 P.M.</a></span><strong>A Growing Crowd in Denver</strong></h5>
</div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">DENVER &#8212; The crowd outside the Capitol here had grown to about three dozen when a woman shouted that Officer Darren Wilson would not be indicted.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Alvertis Simmons, 57, a civil rights activist, threw his hands in the air. âEnough is enough,â he yelled into a circle of Michael Brown supporters, his voice raw and raspy with emotion. The group burst into a enthusiastic call and response: âHands up!â âDonât shoot!â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âOur lives â a black manâs life in America &#8212; means nothing to white Americans,â said Mr. Simmons, who is black. âNothing. We donât mean anything to you all.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe all should have tears in ours right,&#8221; he continued. &#8220;Every last one of you.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One woman called for four and a half  minutes of silence, in honor, she said, of the four and a half hours that Mr. Brown lay in the street after his death.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The group stood silent. Some held hands. Afterward, a woman at the edge of crowd shared her story. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Anita Cameron, 49, said that she was nearly blind and had multiple sclerosis. Her wife urged her not to come to the protest, fearing for her safety. But Ms. Cameron insisted. &#8220;I&#8217;ve been watching the whole thing evolve out of Ferguson,&#8221; said Ms. Cameron, who is black and an activist for the disabled. &#8220;I just had to be here. I couldn&#8217;t sit at home in the comfort of my house.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;I knew they weren&#8217;t going to indict him,&#8221; she said. She struggled to summarize her thoughts. Her voice shook. &#8220;I&#8217;m sad. I&#8217;m angry. I&#8217;m numb. It&#8217;s not unexpected. But it sends a message to people in general, but it certainly sends a message to black folks â our lives don&#8217;t matter.&#8221;</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="in-downtown-ferguson-shattered-glass-and-tear-gas" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#in-downtown-ferguson-shattered-glass-and-tear-gas">10:18 P.M.</a></span><strong>In Downtown Ferguson, Shattered Glass and Tear Gas</strong></h5>
</div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The scene in downtown Ferguson grew increasingly unruly after a group of protesters marched near South Florissant Road shortly before 9 p.m. and focused their anger on a parked St. Louis County Police car that was parked just off the road. They tried to overturn it, but failed, and instead  kicked at the car several times before the police arrived. The protesters threw rocks at the police and broke at least two police car windows. The police responded with tear gas, and a strong odor of the gas permeated the frigid night air.  Nearby, the sound of glass breaking could be heard, apparently the shattering of windows of shuttered businesses. One restaurant, El Palenque, a Mexican restaurant near the Ferguson Police Station, had what appeared to be two broken windows. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>MANNY FERNANDEZ</em></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="sharpton-vows-to-continue-fight" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#sharpton-vows-to-continue-fight">10:04 P.M.</a></span><strong>Sharpton Vows to Continue Fight</strong></h5>
</div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;It was expected,&#8221; the Rev. Al Sharpton, who has served as an unofficial adviser to the Brown family, said of the grand jury&#8217;s decision. &#8220;But still an absolute blow to those of us who worked to see a fair and open trial.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;Ferguson is not just in Missouri,&#8221; he said. &#8220;We can lose a round, but the fight is not over.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When he finished, a shout came from the crowd: &#8220;No justice, no peace!&#8221;</p>
</div>
