<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="reaction-in-chicago" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#reaction-in-chicago">9:55 P.M.</a></span><strong>Reaction in Chicago</strong></h5>
</div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">About 200 people gathered at Chicago Police Headquarters, despite frigid temperatures and light snow.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The crowd was mostly young and mostly white, and some protesters walked around offering coffee. They were holding professionally made signs with slogans like &#8220;From Ferguson to Palestine, occupation is a crime.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When the decision was read, protesters clumped together to watch a television monitor in silence. Cars honked their horns in support as they drove by, but so far, the protest has been peaceful.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>ELLEN ALMER</em></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="emotions-high-at-police-headquarters-2" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#emotions-high-at-police-headquarters-2">9:51 P.M.</a></span><strong>Tears and Anger From Brown&#8217;s Mother</strong></h5>
</div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<div class="w480">
<figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/25/us/FERGUSONBLOG-REACT2/FERGUSONBLOG-REACT2-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
<div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/25/us/FERGUSONBLOG-REACT2/FERGUSONBLOG-REACT2-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/25/us/FERGUSONBLOG-REACT2/FERGUSONBLOG-REACT2-blog480.jpg" id="100000003253985" width="480" height="320" alt="Police officers in riot gear assembled outside the courthouse in Clayton, Mo., after the grand jury announcement on Monday."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div>
<figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Police officers in riot gear assembled outside the courthouse in Clayton, Mo., after the grand jury announcement on Monday.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Whitney Curtis for The New York Times</span></figcaption>
</figure>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As the prosecutor was reading his statment, protesters were listening to it on radios throughout the crowd of hundreds gathered in front of the police station. While the prosecutor was speaking, Mr. Brown&#8217;s mother, Lesley McSpadden, and his stepfather, Louis Head, stepped up onto a platform where protest leaders were standing.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">With a stern look on her face, Ms. McSpadden yelled frustrated responses to what the prosecutor was saying.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âDefend himself from what!â she yelled, when the prosecutor spoke of Officer Darren Wilson. She added that this was a joke, injecting a profanity. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThey wrong!â she yelled, pointing toward the police officers standing outside of the station. âYou all know, you&#8217;re all wrong!â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">She bowed her head and tears started streaming down her cheeks.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âEverybody wants me to be calm,â she said, her eyes covered with sunglasses. âYou know what them bullets did to my son!â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThey still don&#8217;t care!â she yelled. âThey never going to care!â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ms. McSpadden&#8217;s head sank into her husbandâs chest as she wept.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Head then turned and began to yell.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The crowd then roared, with some rushing toward the fence near where the police were lined up. Representatives for the family helped them down off of the platform and ushered them away, through the crowd, and people began dispersing in a moment of anger and chaos. Officers in riot helmets and shields came out. Someone threw a megaphone at the officers.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>JOHN ELIGON</em></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="protesters-brave-cold-in-chicago-3" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#protesters-brave-cold-in-chicago-3">9:56 P.M.</a></span><strong>Protesters Brave Cold in Chicago</strong></h5>
</div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">About 200 people gathered at Chicago Police headquarters, despite frigid temperatures and light snow.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The crowd was mostly young and white. They were holding signs with slogans like &#8220;From Ferguson to Palestine, occupation is a crime.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When the decision was announced, protestors gathered around a television monitor in silence.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Cars honked their horns in support as they drove by.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>ELLEN ALMER</em></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="disbelief-from-some-in-ferguson" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#disbelief-from-some-in-ferguson">10:03 P.M.</a></span><strong>Disbelief From Some in Ferguson</strong></h5>
</div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Some of the few pedestrians on West Florissant Avenue in Ferguson expressed anger and dismay.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;I don&#8217;t even know what to say,&#8221; said Talisha Leopold, 21, who lives in a nearby municipality in St. Louis County.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As cars sped by and revved their engines, she predicted renewed violence, especially as more people learned of the decision.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;Once everyone finds out that he&#8217;s not getting indicted, it&#8217;s going to be war out here,&#8221; she said. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ke&#8217;Yanna Hinkle, 19, sounded a similar warning.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;It&#8217;s about to go down,&#8221; she said. &#8220;It&#8217;s about to go down.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">She added: &#8220;It&#8217;s going to be everywhere.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>ALAN BLINDER</em></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="anger-in-new-york-city-2" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#anger-in-new-york-city-2">9:58 P.M.</a></span><strong>Anger in New York City</strong></h5>
</div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">About 300 people at Union Square Park in Manhattan waited quietly for 20 minutes, many with fists raised in the air, before the decision was released, then exploded with angry chants once the news was announced by several people n the crowd.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;Hands up, don&#8217;t shoot,&#8221; protesters yelled as they rattled police barricades, then surged onto University Place, shutting down traffic while they stormed toward Washington Square Park. Police officers followed on motorbikes as a helicopter hovered overhead.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;Its a continuation of what&#8217;s been going on forever in the Unite States of America, like slavery, lynching, unequal voting,&#8221; said Walter Gafforio, 71, a Vietnam veteran from West Babylon, on Long Island, who came in to Manhattan to await the verdict. &#8220;We can&#8217;t just let the killing continue. These are American youth.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>C. J. HUGHES</em></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="in-oakland-protesters-express-bitterness-2" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#in-oakland-protesters-express-bitterness-2">9:55 P.M.</a></span><strong>In Oakland, Protesters Express Bitterness</strong></h5>
</div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<div class="w480">
<figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/25/us/FERGUSONBLOG-OAKLAND1/FERGUSONBLOG-OAKLAND1-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
<div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/25/us/FERGUSONBLOG-OAKLAND1/FERGUSONBLOG-OAKLAND1-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/25/us/FERGUSONBLOG-OAKLAND1/FERGUSONBLOG-OAKLAND1-blog480.jpg" id="100000003254025" width="480" height="320" alt="Protesters outside City HallÂ in Oakland, Calif.,Â reacted to the grand jury decision."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div>
<figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Protesters outside City HallÂ in Oakland, Calif.,Â reacted to the grand jury decision.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Jim Wilson/The New York Times</span></figcaption>
</figure>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In Oakland, a crowd of several dozen demonstrators staged a march  downtown. Terry Malbrough, 23, a local college student said: &#8220;I&#8217;m here because I can relate to what&#8217;s going on. This is nothing new, you know? This happened in Oakland all the time. I feel like it&#8217;s just becoming popular in a sense. That could have been me. I&#8217;m here in solidarity with the family of Mike Brown.&#8221; </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Karen McClelland, 69, who described herself as a &#8220;white person of European descent&#8221; came with a group of fellow members from a Unitarian church.They wore yellow T-shirts that said &#8220;Standing on the Side of Love.&#8221;  She has not attended many rallies, but felt moved to head out to the street as a result of the grand jury&#8217;s decision. &#8220;I&#8217;m devastated,&#8221; Ms. McClelland said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;We wanted to be here because what happened. We don&#8217;t want it to happen again. The names of the young men who died keep running through my head,&#8221; referring to a list of young men killed by the police. &#8220;Coming out and being visible is one thing an individual person can do. It&#8217;s important for us to take a stand when wrong things are happening.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>MOMO CHANG</em></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="anger-and-disbelief-in-harlem" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#anger-and-disbelief-in-harlem">9:46 P.M.</a></span><strong>Anger and Disbelief in Harlem</strong></h5>
</div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<div class="w480">
<figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/25/us/FERGUSONBLOG-GARNER/FERGUSONBLOG-GARNER-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
<div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/25/us/FERGUSONBLOG-GARNER/FERGUSONBLOG-GARNER-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/25/us/FERGUSONBLOG-GARNER/FERGUSONBLOG-GARNER-blog480.jpg" id="100000003253995" width="480" height="320" alt="The Rev. Al Sharpton at the headquarters of the National Action Network, in New York."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div>
<figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">The Rev. Al Sharpton at the headquarters of the National Action Network, in New York.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Sam Hodgson for The New York Times</span></figcaption>
</figure>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At the headquarters in Harlem of the National Action Network, which is headed by the Rev. Al Sharpton, the reaction to the news from a crowd of over 100 people included hisses, groans and a shout of &#8220;What?&#8221; when the announcement came via MSNBC that Officer Darren Wilson would not be indicted in the shooting death of Michael Brown. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Dozens shook their heads with pained expressions on their faces. Mr. Sharpton had served as an adviser to Mr. Brown&#8217;s family. Mr. Sharpton was at his group&#8217;s headquarters with the family of Eric Garner, a Staten Island man who died after he was placed in what appeared to be a choke hold by a New York City police officer. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A grand jury is weighing evidence in that case.  Mr. Garner&#8217;s family said they had lost all hope of ever seeing justice.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>NATE SCHWEBER</em></p>
</div>
</div>
