<div id="a-small-crowd-gathers-in-denver-2" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#a-small-crowd-gathers-in-denver-2">8:39 P.M.</a></span><strong>A Small Crowd in Denver</strong></h5>
</div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">DENVER &#8212; The scene here was calm but impassioned. By 6 p.m. Mountain time, about two dozen people had gathered in a park across from the state Capitol, saying they were there to show support for the family of Michael Brown.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Several held a giant red banner: âYour âpeaceâ is deadly.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As buses drove past, Alvertis Simmons, 57, a long-time civil rights activist, said Mr. Brownâs death had stirred the country to action, and he vowed to continue fighting for changes in police policy, no matter the grand jury&#8217;s decision in Missouri. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThis is a movement,â he said. âThis is not a moment. This is a movement.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe police come into our community, they mistreat black and brown people,â said Mr. Simmons, who is black. âThey treat us as second-class citizens, and weâre going to change that by exercising our First Amendment right. Thatâs why weâre out here in this bitter cold.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Kenny Wiley, 26, stood nearby. After Mr. Brown&#8217;s death, Mr. Wiley took to Twitter to find other Coloradans who were also angered by the incident, and he found Jo Cusick, a white nurse. The two started a group called Coloradans for Justice.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Since then, the group has organized five events in support of the Brown  family, including one that drew 350 people, Mr. Wiley said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âFor me personally, that could be me,â he said. âTo me, Mike Brown could have been anybody. Iâm a college graduate, I speak respectably, my pants are up, but in the wrong situation that could have been me as well. And I just felt called to act.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>JULIE TURKEWITZ</em></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="cold-and-work-to-keep-some-protesters-home" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#cold-and-work-to-keep-some-protesters-home">8:38 P.M.</a></span><strong>Cold, and Work, to Keep Some Protesters Home</strong></h5>
</div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Dozens of protesters already started to gather outside the Ferguson Police Department on Monday night in advance of the announcement of the grand jury decision. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/11/22/us/this-time-the-protesters-in-ferguson-may-decide-to-pass.html?module=Search&#038;mabReward=relbias%3As%2C{%221%22%3A%22RI%3A5%22}">But John Eligon reported</a> that some protesters who participated in past demonstrations said they were unlikely to join them again because of the cold weather or because they could not afford to miss work. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The temperature in St. Louis on Monday night was 40 degrees, with a low of 27 expected, according to The Weather Channel.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>EMMA G. FITZSIMMONS</em></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="police-are-prepared-chief-says-2" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#police-are-prepared-chief-says-2">8:19 P.M.</a></span><strong>Police Are Prepared, Chief Says </strong></h5>
</div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<div class="w480">
<figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/25/us/FERGUSONBLOG-PROTESTS1/FERGUSONBLOG-PROTESTS1-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
<div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/25/us/FERGUSONBLOG-PROTESTS1/FERGUSONBLOG-PROTESTS1-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/25/us/FERGUSONBLOG-PROTESTS1/FERGUSONBLOG-PROTESTS1-blog480.jpg" id="100000003253806" width="480" height="320" alt="Protesters outside the Ferguson police station on Monday.Â "   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div>
<figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Protesters outside the Ferguson police station on Monday.Â </span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Whitney Curtis for The New York Times</span></figcaption>
</figure>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">FERGUSON, Mo. &#8212; Less than an hour before the St. Louis County prosecutor was to announce the grand jury&#8217;s decison, the county&#8217;s police chief said officers were prepared for the reaction.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;Our primary responsibility is to protect both life and property for our citizens, and we are committed to doing just that,&#8221; the chief, Jon Belmar, said in a statement.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He added: &#8220;Our commanders have been meeting with local community officials and protest leaders to help ensure preservation of life, property and that all citizens enjoy the freedom to express their constitutional rights.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Protesters sharply criticized the police response to the demonstrations in August, and they have often said that the behavior of law enforcement officials may be a factor in how far the protests go after the grand jury&#8217;s decision is made public.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>ALAN BLINDER</em></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="why-make-the-announcement-at-night-2" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#why-make-the-announcement-at-night-2">8:19 P.M.</a></span><strong>Why Make the Announcement at Night?</strong></h5>
</div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">While we wait for the grand jury&#8217;s decision, Twitter users are wondering why the announcement was being made in the evening. </p>
