<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="for-darren-wilson-no-news-2" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#for-darren-wilson-no-news-2">6:30 P.M.</a></span><strong>For Darren Wilson, No News</strong></h5>
</div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A person close to Officer Wilson said that by 5 p.m. Central time, the officer had not received a call from the prosecutor&#8217;s office informing him of an indictment. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Officer Wilson&#8217;s lawyers had previously made arrangements with the prosecutor&#8217;s office planning for the possibility that he would be indicted. If the grand jury returned an indictment, Officer Wilson was expecting to receive a phone call asking him to turn himself in.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Officer Wilson was planning to voluntarily surrender if he was indicted. So far, he has not been asked to do so, the person close to him said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>JULIE BOSMAN</em></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="rallies-planned-in-atlanta" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#rallies-planned-in-atlanta">6:26 P.M.</a></span><strong>Rallies Planned in Atlanta</strong></h5>
</div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In Atlanta on Monday night, civil rights leaders, student activists and local law enforcement were inside an old fire station that is part of the Martin Luther King Jr. National Historic Site, just yards from the slain civil rights leader&#8217;s tomb.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Their agenda &#8212; as it so often has been in this cradle of the civil rights movement &#8212; was how to make sure that angry and frustrated voices could be heard, while also keeping the peace.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the middle of the meeting, the Rev. Markel Hutchins came downstairs and gave a brief news conference, saying he was confident that Atlantans would react peacefully to the Missouri grand juryâs decision, no matter what it was.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âAtlanta is unlike any other city in the nation and in fact in the world,&#8221; Mr.  Hutchins said. &#8220;We know how to do demonstrations. We know how to do direct action. And we know how to sit at the table of brotherhood and sisterhood. We saw what happened in Ferguson with the lack of communication between law enforcement and community organizations. We saw a lack of leadership in one real sense. We are determined not to let that happen in the city of Atlanta.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;This is Martin Luther King Jr.âs town. We are met right here in the King District because we want to set an appropriate tone of how we work together as brothers and sisters whether weâre law enforcement, civil rights, students or whatever we are.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Civil rights leaders in Atlanta were planning on holding a rally outside of the cityâs downtown federal court building on Monday, said Faye Coffield, a human rights activist and retired Atlanta Police sergeant, who left a closed-door meeting of civil rights leaders and the police.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ms. Coffield dismissed the idea that Atlanta would see any violence. âThis ainât Ferguson,â said Ms. Coffield, the chairwoman of the criminal justice committee of The Peopleâs Agenda, a civil rights group. &#8220;You ainât going to see no dogs. You ainât going to see no tanks.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Hutchins also said that civil rights groups were deciding whether to go ahead with a planned rally on Monday night in front of the federal court building in downtown Atlanta. He said they were planning other peaceful protests for the downtown district on Tuesday night.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>RICHARD FAUSSET</em></p>
</div>
</div>
